  "text": "The PK parameters obtained following cobalt chloride administration in the current study are consistent with those obtained in a previous study by Knych et al. [CITATION_1] that investigated the PK of a single administration of cobalt chloride (49 mg Co; Table 2 ). In the previous study, cobalt chloride was infused i.v. over a 10-min period and in this situation it is imperative that PK samples are taken during the infusion period. Based upon the alpha half-life found previously [CITATION_2] , it was estimated that a reasonable back extrapolation for the PK parameter, V1, would be obtained from a first sample point taken at 15-min post-bolus administration so as to reduce the number of blood samples taken. The mean clearance value obtained by Knych et al. [CITATION_3] was slightly higher than found in the current CoCl 2 study which would not be the case if the early portion of the AUC was missed. In both the current and previous studies, cobalt chloride clearance and terminal half-life parameters (Table 2 ) are larger (39) and shorter (29), respectively, compared with the parameters obtained for the lower cobalt 'dose' present in the vitamin B 12 /cobalt preparation administration ( Table 1 ). The higher clearance value for the single administration of cobalt chloride (49 mg Co) relative to the administration of the vitamin B 12 /cobalt preparation used in the current study may be due to a reduction in cobalt reabsorption from the kidney back to blood. The dose used for the vitamin B 12 /cobalt preparation was the recommended dose of this product, licensed for use in many countries. The single dose of cobalt chloride was representative of a 'doping' dose that could affect performance and have adverse side effects. This 'doping' dose was based upon doses in human subjects which have shown increases in EPO and was the same as the dose used in the Knych (2012) study. The PK argument put forward is that there is only one possible explanation for the clearance to be higher for the higher dose cobalt chloride administration relative to the vitamin B 12 / cobalt preparation, i.e. the reabsorption mechanism from urine to blood is saturated for high concentrations of cobalt in the urine but for lower doses (and lower urine levels) reabsorption returns to first order kinetics. In plasma, the threshold of 25 ng/mL is only exceeded for a couple of hours after the administration of the current vitamin B 12 /cobalt preparation, whereas urine concentrations drop below the 100 ng/mL threshold by approximately 8 h. Based upon the predicted accumulation (Table 3) , it would be highly unlikely that any increase in urine concentration would exceed a 100 ng/mL urine screening limit with a once a day regimen of the current vitamin B 12 /cobalt preparation or equivalent dose cobalt supplement. However, based on a Monte Carlo simulation (data not shown), the 25 ng/mL plasma threshold could potentially be breached in a population of horses with a once a day regimen of a vitamin B 12 /cobalt supplement or equivalent dose cobalt supplement. Therefore, practitioners should continue to advise caution when using these products in racehorses.",
